==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cyanogen
<hw>Cy*an"o*gen</hw> <pr>(s?-?n"?-j?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>ky`anos</grk> a dark blue substance + <ets>-gen</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>cyanog⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>. So called because it produced blue
dyes.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A colorless, inflammable, poisonous
gas, <chform>C2N2</chform>, with a peach-blossom odor, so called from
its tendency to form <xex>blue</xex> compounds; obtained by heating
ammonium oxalate, mercuric cyanide, etc. It is obtained in combination,
forming an alkaline cyanide when nitrogen or a nitrogenous compound is
strongly ignited with carbon and soda or potash. It conducts itself like
a member of the halogen group of elements, and shows a tendency to form
complex compounds. The name is also applied to the univalent radical,
<chform>CN</chform> (the half molecule of cyanogen proper), which was
one of the first compound radicals recognized.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Cyanogen</ex> is found in the commercial substances,
potassium cyanide, or prussiate of potash, yellow prussiate of potash,
Prussian blue, Turnbull's blue, prussic acid, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

